---
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <meta name="generator" content={Astro.generator} />
    <title>About — School Trust Lands Encyclopedia</title>
  </head>
  <body class="min-h-screen bg-slate-50 text-slate-900">
    <Header />
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-prose p-4 sm:p-8">
      <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
        <h1>About this encyclopedia</h1>

        <p>
          The School Trust Lands Encyclopedia is a state-by-state reference on the
          federal land grants, constitutional architecture, permanent funds, and
          ongoing fiduciary disputes that shape American school trust lands. Each
          entry traces one state's trust from its admission act through its present
          corpus, governance form, and live litigation. The encyclopedia is
          organized into six era cohorts mirroring the synthesizing argument in
          <em>Schools of the Republic</em>.
        </p>

        <h2>Who is behind this</h2>

        <p>
          The site is operated by an interim entity, the Operating Advocates for
          School Trust Lands (OASTL), pending the formal adoption of a successor
          organization, Advocates for School Trust Lands (ASTL). OASTL exists to
          carry the public-facing scholarship and advocacy work forward without
          waiting on the corporate steps. Editorial responsibility currently rests
          with Dave Sullivan and Margaret Bird; the substrate and synthesis are
          their joint work.
        </p>

        <h2>Methodology</h2>

        <p>
          Each entry is generated from a hand-curated source document — the v0.4
          substrate — held in a private repository and never published verbatim.
          A Python migration script extracts the bibliographic frontmatter and a
          subset of quantitative fields (federal grant acres, governance form,
          permanent-fund corpus, latest distribution) and renders each state as an
          Astro content page. The migration is merge-preserving: hand-edited values
          on the website are never overwritten by re-running the script. The site
          is a static build; there is no database and no server-side runtime.
        </p>

        <h2>Known limitations</h2>

        <p>
          As of substrate v1.3, only one state (Oregon) has fully hand-verified
          financial figures in the page header. The other forty-nine carry partial
          data: most have a federal grant acreage and a governance description,
          but permanent-fund corpus and latest-distribution figures are populated
          only when the substrate value is unambiguous and pinned to a date. Where
          a year is given but no calendar day, the date field is left null rather
          than fabricated.
        </p>

        <p>
          The visual design is interim. There is no logo, no signature typeface,
          and no brand color system; those decisions are deferred until Margaret
          can weigh in on the public identity. The library architecture — sources,
          jurisdictions, table-of-authorities cross-references — is pending and
          will replace the current flat footnote structure on each entry.
        </p>

        <h2>How to cite</h2>

        <p>
          Cite individual entries as: <em>Sullivan and Bird, Schools of the
          Republic v1.3, schooltrustlands.net/states/&#123;slug&#125;/, retrieved
          YYYY-MM-DD.</em> A pre-filled citation appears in the footer of every
          page.
        </p>

        <h2>Contact and corrections</h2>

        <p>
          The site source — including this page and the migration scripts — lives on
          <a href="https://github.com/dave-schooltrustlands/schooltrustlands-encyclopedia"
            >GitHub</a
          >. Open an issue there for corrections, citation requests, or
          methodology questions.
        </p>
      </article>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
